b.com/users/dannon/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/dannon/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"body":"Primary driver was fixing the deployed MSA application on main -- this has been deployed to main in the usegalaxy branch as of last week and is working well to resolve our issues w/ msa.  Specifying node package dependencies and relying on prebuilt visualization plugins (as implemented here) is going to make a huge difference in reliability moving forward.

In short, visualizations should prebuild and publish a `static` directory with whatever they need to run.

In package.json, that's this new part:

```
    "files": [
        "static"
    ],
```

Then the viz is published to npm like so:  https://www.npmjs.com/@galaxyproject/msa

And then in the viz xml, we specify a particular version (or range, as appropriate) of plugin the viz is compatible with, like so:

```
    <requirements>
        <requirement type="package" version="0.2.1" package="@galaxyproject/msa"/>
    </requirements>
```

These requirements will all get staged to the Galaxy server's static file serving *without a build process required*, avoiding all of the issues we've had with differing node versions on novel and/or archaic systems.


